Great free puzzle game released back in 2008 that inspired the paint mechanics of Portal 2. Glad to see it released on Steam 14 years later so that those who never played it back then (such as myself) could find out about it.

Only caveat being that I wish there was a save mechanic. I was several levels in (presumably towards/at the end) when I tabbed out to send a message to someone and managed to freeze the game in the process. When I reopened it, I was back at the start of the game.

Tag: The Power of Paint is a game that uses three different colors of paint and gives them each a different special ability. The green paint is produced by Up Enterprise and makes you jump once stood on. The red paint is produced by Fast Firm and makes you fast once walked on. The most unique being the blue paint which is produced by Disorientation Corporation and can make you stand sideways or even upside down. While the game is good it lacks a story of any kind is not that long at all.

To put it lightly, it's a fun game and if you have the time you should play it. Also, for a game made by some students it was done really good (Way better than me, I can't even code). It had a very fun idea and worked on it in many fun ways. However, I have two "complaints" I want to bring up. In the stick power sections I found it very sickening (big word for me), the camera either changed too often or changed to fast making me take a break here and there so I don't throw up. The only other "complaint" I have is how you have no control sometimes. Like no way to move yourself in the air for the jump power and sometimes, no way to stop moving with the speed power. However, I'm willing to look past these things I brought up cause overall the concept of this game is amazing. Like I said earlier, play it if you're able to, you'll enjoy it for sure.

√âvaluation publi√©e le 18 mai 2022
The game that caught Valve's attention during development of Portal 2. Much like Portal 2, it features differently coloured paint (later, gel) for bouncing, speed and climbing onto surfaces, the difference being the blue (climbing) paint and the paint gun, later included in the Portal 2 mod Aperture Tag. It's fun but short, short enough that no saving system was implemented.

Sadly, while the game has replay value for speedrunning, floaty air movement and frequent hitching make it tedious to play, but it's short enough that it's not a huge issue for a normal playthrough.

I is an extremely well done, simple puzzle game (one precursor for Portal series). While it can be done well within the hour both the physics and the aesthetics are excellent, it's fun to look around and just playing with the environment (painting the clouds is probably compulsory). Also the puzzles are not hard, which balances the fact that there is no save.
I really would like to see a higher resolution, longer full game about it. Well, apart from Portal of course. ;-)

√âvaluation publi√©e le 29 novembre 2023
Very short but fun little puzzle platformer. Decent music too.

I didn't experience the crashes others did, but it's true that there is no save that persists between game sessions, nor is there a level select I could find. There are checkpoints while playing the game so you don't have to redo long sections of levels, and the whole game is short, taking me less than an hour.

The only other caveat is that the paint that sticks you to surfaces reorients the camera. You can't turn this off, and it might give you motion sickness even if you're not usually susceptible to that.

√âvaluation publi√©e le 26 juin 2023
Wonderful game filled with 2000's energy. Honestly I loved a lot of how the colors of the paints contrast with the otherwise colorless world, it's fairly simple, yet, fairly unique. The soundtrack is also really something to talk about, it's great electronic music with energy and great direction. There's a reason why this game was looked at by Valve for inspiration of the gel in Portal 2, it's short so it won't take up too much of your time, yet, it also has some nice game design. There were a few bugs, mostly with the stick paint. But other than that, it's a great game that I think everyone who is interested in game design should play. It's intuitive, and quite impressive for a small project.

Produit re√ßu gratuitement

It's a free 35 minute long game made by a group of students at Digipen and is the inspiration for the paint in Portal 2. (Narbacular Drop, the inspiration for Portal, was made by a different group at the same college a few years earlier.)

If you've played Portal 2, most of the tricks (like the speed paint run + bounce ramp combo) are here as well, the blue paint was changed entirely and is my main complaint. The way it automatically tilts your camera up 90 degrees when you switch surfaces is annoying and it sometimes launches you away from ledges. Other than that, it's a fun short experience.

I bet the class that put together what was supposed to be just a student project didn't expect it to end up serving as one of Portal 2's inspirations. If you're interested in Portal's history and/or what influenced the game, this is worth checking out.

If you liked the gel mechanics in Portal 2, I would highly recommend this game, but if you've never played Portal 2, firstly, play Portal 2, but secondly, this is a simple puzzle platformer where you can shoot different colours of paint that have different effects. The red paint makes you go fast, the green paint makes you bounce, and the blue paint makes you stick to walls.

You'll get a decent amount of play out of this and I'd highly recommend this game!

Game developed by students from the DigiPen Institute of Technology
Honestly, this game is pretty impressive, specially considering it was just a student project! Reminds me a lot of Aperture Tag, my favourite Portal 2 mod ever, so that's good. Also, the cell shaded artstyle and low-poly models mixed with the paint mechanic, give it a hint of JSR, and that's also pretty cool.

Levels are fun, mechanics are neat, artstyle is pleasent... everything checks. Great job!

Admittedly, Tag is more of tech demo and student project than a full game. It's fun, though. It's worth playing from the perspective of learning more about the development history of Portal 2, and just for seeing a particular game concept explored. It has a neat graffiti sensibility, and it's fun to run and bounce around its rooftop world. After about 40 minutes I felt I had gotten everything I wanted from it, which you might find good, or bad; personally I think it's fine. And also...y'know, it's free!
 
Cultist John

√âvaluation publi√©e le 10 mai 2022
Competent.
Initially too derivative of Portal 2's water/bounce/speed gels, but the blue sticky gel adds something.

The FOV is a little too tight, so after a couple of bounces, you get disoriented quickly (worse than Mirror's Edge).
The in-air movement should be a little stronger. It's quite frustrating when you've worked out the path, but you missed jump #5 AGAIN and have to do #1 to #4 again.
When doing corner transitions with sticky gel, the camera motion feels off somehow. I'm not sure exactly how to improve it, but it feels very mechanical and not fluid. Maybe need to make the transition speed a bell curve instead of linear, so it starts and ends gradually, but is fast in the middle? Have a look at what someone else has done with this? Wall transitions are common in Tremulous and in Alien games (where you play facehuggers).

PS: needs an "invert Y axis" option. I pull the mouse back because I'm pulling on my character's head to make them look up. I'm not dragging their eyes down to look down.
 
Trent W. Buck

I dont know how I managed to stumble upon this gem - however, I do know that this game blew my mind

At first I expected a jet set radio inspired game with the graphics, overall premise and title fitting the bill. But this game has so much charm and creativity packed into such a small package that I cant rest without having made a comment on it.
The campaign is fairly short - I managed to beat it in just about 40 minutes
You have three colours at your disposal, which you unlock further into the levels
Now, the interesting part is that for each colour, your character will do a different action.
The puzzles are just right and accomplish the colours quite well

My favourite part have to be the credits, definitely going into my favourites

I looked every where for this game because I fondly remember playing it as a kid and painting absolutly everything on every map. I never found it because I just remebered it being called tag and well when you look up tag on google you get graffiti. But I recently found out the whole name and bam, it pops up on steam.

I strongly recommend this game.
